            <pb n="1"/>

            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName>&#44; <date>May 25<hi rend="sup">th</hi>
                    5608</date></p>
            <p>Reverend Sir&#33;</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have the honor&#44; to send you hereby a small article<lb/> for your
                &#8220;Occident&#44;&#8221; and after having read it you may<lb/> decide of its
                being worthy to be published. Believing&#44;<lb/> as I do&#44; you will agree with
                me&#44; contending&#44; that<lb/> a comparison of the present struggle with
                that<lb/> of <persName>Maimonides</persName> is not improper&#44; I should
                think&#44; it<lb/> will also appease some pious minds excited<lb/> by the present
                state of our eternal religion.<lb/> My English expression &#40;style&#41; will
                acquire many<lb/> corrections and you will have the kindness to do so.<lb/> I was
                taking care to express myself as distinctly<lb/> as possible&#44; but a
                foreigner&#8212;as I am&#44; only two<lb/> years in this country&#44; it will
                require your issue.<lb/> To the blaming Article of &#8220;truth&#44;&#8221; who
                amongst<lb/> other mistakes also pretends&#58; &#8220;the <del>reading</del>
                <hi rend="underline">annual</hi><lb/> reading of the Pentateuch was already
                introduced<lb/> by <persName>Ezra the Scribe</persName>&#44;&#8221; I furnish you
                the following<lb/> passage taken of <add>Hebrew</add>&#58; <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                &#8220;some congregations use to read the Pentateuch but once<lb/> in three
                years.&#8221;&#8212; <persName>R. Benjamin de Tudela</persName> says&#58;<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add></p>
            <p>Do these passages not prove&#44; that &#8220;<add>Hebrew</add>&#8221; is
                    <add>Hebrew</add>&#63;&#44; that<lb/>
                <persName>Ezra the Scribe</persName> did not introduce the <hi rend="underline"
                    >annual<lb/> reading</hi></p>

            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>reading of the Pentateuch&#44; or else the <addressee>Hebrew</addressee><lb/> surely
                followed him and not read the P. but once<lb/> in three years.
                    <persName>Ezra</persName> did introduce&#44; that they<lb/> <del>set</del> should read in
                the Pentateuch in generally&#44; he<lb/> also ordered&#58; <add>Hebrew</add> of. Gemara<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add> f. 82. 1.&#59; but to <del>read</del> finish the P. in one year<lb/> whence
                will <del>fr</del> &#8220;truth&#8221; prove&#44; that <persName>Ezra</persName> has
                    order<add>ed</add><lb/> so&#63; I can prove the contrary. The Gemara says<lb/>
                in <add>Hebrew</add>&#58; <add>Hebrew</add> &#8220;the <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> the
                Palestinian Jews read the Pentateuch but once<lb/> in three years.&#8221; Proves
                that not distinctly<lb/> against &#8220;truth&#8221;&#63; No doubt&#44; <hi rend="underline">many</hi>
                centuries af<add>ter</add>]<lb/>
                <persName>Ezra</persName> in <placeName>Palestine</placeName> and other countries
                the P. was read but once in<lb/> three years and in
                    <placeName><sic>Babylonien</sic></placeName> the reading in<lb/> one year was
                instituted probably <hi rend="underline">700 or 800 year<add>s</add></hi><lb/> after. <persName>Ezra the
                    Scribe</persName>. Please&#44; Sir&#44; make use of<lb/> <del>it</del> these remarks in
                your &#8220;Occident&#44;&#8221; you may <add>&#63;</add><lb/> upon my
                quotations&#44; I <del>have</del> shall send you in<lb/> future contributions for your paper
                but now&#44; Sir&#44;<lb/> I stop&#44; <add>Hebrew</add>&#8212;and besides that&#44;
                I do not<lb/> know&#44; how you are pleased with my com<add>m</add>encement<lb/>
                Most respectfully<lb/> Yours<lb/>
                <persName role="author">Dr Kohlmeyer</persName></p>
            <p>Rev. <addressee>I. Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>


